
    NOTE: in these crazy times, I must tell you that I did not use an LLM
    for any part of this codebase or document.
    I wrote it all myself, except where I explicitly give sources.
    - Ben Ayers-Glassey, 2026


###############################################################################
### MINITASKS

It's a miniature multi-tasking operating system for the Arduino Nano, which is
a little computer-on-a-chip.
See also:
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arduino

The purpose of this project is to let me experiment with the Arduino from my
laptop, examining its memory on the fly, and sending it little programs to run,
either as one-off commands or as concurrent tasks, with observable behaviour
like toggling LEDs and sending bytes back over USB etc.
Basically, it's a way to learn about embedded programming and realtime OS
implementation.

My Arduino Nano is technically an "Elegoo Nano V3.0", which is built from the
Arduino Nano specs.
The microchip is an ATmega 328P, which is part of the "AVR" family of
chips.
The core "minitasks" system (the multi-tasking OS) is written in C and
assembly, using the standard AVR development toolchain: avr-gcc, avr-libc,
avrdude, etc.
See also:
* https://www.nongnu.org/avr-libc/
* https://github.com/avrdudes/avr-libc
* https://github.com/avrdudes/avrdude

The core of the OS (scheduler, resource queues, etc) is written in C.
See: minitasks.h, minitasks.c.

The commands/tasks you send to the OS use a tiny programming language, called
"tasklang", written in assembly. It's described more fully below.
See: tasklang.py (for the compiler), tasklang.S (for the runtime)

The client (which runs on my/your laptop, and talks to the OS over USB) is
written in Python.
See: minitasks.py


###############################################################################
### THE "TASKLANG" LANGUAGE

The "minitasks" system consists of a Python client sending little programs
over USB to the OS on the Arduino, to be run as tasks.
These little programs are written in a language called "tasklang".

The language is vaguely FORTH-like: it's explicitly stack-based, and uses
"threaded code" as its execution model, that is, "code" consists of arrays of
pointers representing subroutine calls.
However, unlike FORTH, tasklang doesn't come with its own compiler; instead,
programs are compiled by the Python client (see tasklang.py), and the OS only
needs to know how to run them.
See also:
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forth_(programming_language)
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Threaded_code

NOTE: why use threaded code?.. why not compile to machine code on the fly?..
Because the microchip uses the "Harvard architecture", i.e. programs and data
have separate address spaces.
Specifically, programs live in flash memory, which can only be written to a
page at a time by the bootloader.
So, compiling small programs on-the-fly is not possible, or at any rate not
straightforward (you would need to write a custom bootloader, and then either
use an entire page of flash for every program, or do something fancy like
copy pages out of flash into SRAM, append freshly-compiled code, then copy
them back into flash).

The language is very simple: everything is an integer, integers can also be
interpreted as pointers, all variables are global, and there is no support
for defining new functions/subroutines, only for calling built-in ones written
in assembly.

However, the purpose of the language isn't to be expressive, but to be easy
to reason about and debug, and just powerful enough to play with multitasking
concepts like scheduling, resources, and inter-task communcation.

Here's an example program, which does some math and then ends:

    # Set x to 1 + 2.
    # The "1" and "2" literals push their values onto the stack.
    # The "+" operator pops 2 values off the stack, adds them together,
    # and pushes the result onto the stack.
    # For more information, read any basic FORTH tutorial!..
    # As for "=x", that's not standard FORTH syntax: it means "pop a value
    # from the stack and store it in the x variable".
    1 2 + =x

    # Set y to x * x.
    # The meaning of "dup" is "duplicate the value on top of the stack", so
    # "x dup" is equivalent to "x x".
    x dup * =y

    # Assert that x equals 3, and y equals 9.
    # If an assertion fails, the task is stopped, but hangs around in memory
    # so you can inspect it if you want.
    x 3 == assert
    y 9 == assert

Here's another example program, which runs as a long-lived task.
Its behaviour is to blink the Arduino's built-in LED on and off, once per
second:

    # Set the variable "led_state" to 0
    0 =led_state

    # Start an infinite loop
    loop {
        # Call the set_led function with one argument, the desired LED state
        # (0 for off, 1 for on)
        led_state set_led

        # Reverse the desired LED state
        led_state ! =led_state

        # Ask the OS to put this task to sleep & wake it up in 1 second
        sleep 1000
    }

Here's another example program.
NOTE: Running a program creates a task with at least two associated byte
streams: stdin and stdout (standard input/output).
Streams can be hooked up directly to the Arduino's USB port, i.e. the Python
client, or they can be hooked up to other tasks.

    # Set msg to point at the current top of the heap.
    # Every task has a stack and a heap, which grow towards each other.
    # All variables are 16-bit integers, which can also be interpreted as
    # as pointers.
    heap =msg

    loop {
        # Call getc, putting this task to sleep & waking it up once a
        # byte is available on its stdin
        getc =c

        # Push c onto the heap as a single byte
        c hpushc

        # If c was a NUL byte, exit the loop
        c while
    }

    # At this point, msg points to a C-style string on the heap!..
    # Now we're going to repeatedly echo it back over stdout.
    # For fun, we'll keep track of how many times we echo it.
    0 =n_echoes

    loop {

        # Set ptr to msg, i.e. the start of the string
        msg =ptr

        # Loop over the characters in the string
        loop {
            # Dereference ptr, getting a byte, and store that in c
            ptr $c =c

            # Break on NUL byte
            c while

            # Call putc, putting c in this task's stdout buffer, then
            # putting this task to sleep & waking it up once the byte has
            # been consumed
            c putc

            # Increment ptr
            ptr 1 + =ptr
        }

        # Increment our echo counter
        n_echoes 1 + =n_echoes

        # Logging is sent directly through the USB to the Python client,
        # using low-level assembly routines.
        # That is, tasks don't have a separate stderr stream, rather logging
        # is atomic and bypasses the OS.
        # Why?.. because logging is for debugging purposes, of course!
        # It would be harder to debug the OS if logging was tied up with it...
        # Anyway, if we want to log a dynamic message, we don't build a string
        # on the heap!.. we log it in parts.
        # We can use an atomic block to make sure other tasks don't log (or do
        # anything else) while we're logging.
        atomic {
            "Echoed " logs
            msg logs
            ' ' logc
            n_echoes logi
            " times!\n" logs
        }
    }


###############################################################################
### TASK MEMORY LAYOUT

The OS consists of a kernel, and whatever tasks are running.
There is a task table of fixed size:

    struct task TASKS[MAX_TASKS];

Each task has an id, which is just its index within the table.
MAX_TASKS is <= 256, so a task id fits in a single byte.
The task structure looks like this in memory:

    +--------+------+------+------+-------+
    | FIELDS | CODE | HEAP | FREE | STACK |
    +--------+------+------+------+-------+

    <-------- sizeof struct task --------->

Where:
* FIELDS are fields used by the OS for bookkeeping, etc
  (e.g. task's state: stopped/started/sleeping/etc)
* CODE is the "threaded code" compiled from tasklang, i.e. an array of
  pointers to small assembly routines implementing the basic "instructions"
  of the tasklang runtime
* HEAP grows upwards
* FREE is free space, used by HEAP and STACK when they grow
* STACK grows downwards

The heap and stack grow towards each other, and there are no stack overflow
checks.
In fact, while a task is running, the microchip's stack pointer is set to
the top of that task's stack, and any assembly routines called by the task
(or triggered by interrupts!..) use that task's stack space.


###############################################################################
### OS/CLIENT COMMUNICATION PROTOCOL

The kernel assumes it always has a USB connection to the Python client.
This USB connection gives us two byte streams, the "input stream" from client
to OS, and the "output stream" from OS to client.
The OS kernel and tasks use these streams for different purposes: the kernel
uses them to exchange messages with the client (this is how e.g. tasks are
created, stopped, inspected, etc), while tasks use them as plain byte streams,
essentially the equivalent of C's stdin/stdout.
Basically, tasks "think" they are using the USB streams directly, but in fact
the kernel is able to exchange messages over the same connection.
The input/output streams are a "resource" shared by all tasks: if one task
sends the characters "abc", and another task concurrently sends "123", those
characters are sent over the shared output stream interleaved according to
the whims of the scheduler, e.g. "abc123", "123abc", "a12bc3", etc.
The client cannot distinguish between tasks on the other end of the
input/output streams.

A protocol is used to multiplex kernel messages and task data:
* By default, data is assumed to be going to/from tasks
* Messages to/from the kernel are sent "atomically" (i.e. they block tasks
  from using the raw USB streams), and begin with the escape character 0xFF
  followed by a message type id (one byte), followed by data specific to that
  message type, which may involve bidirectional data exchange between client
  and kernel, and may be "streaming", i.e. of unknown length
* When the escape character is to be sent to/from a task, it appears doubled
  in the raw USB stream: 0xFF 0xFF
* Escape character "doubling" is handled transparently by the client and OS;
  tasks only "see" a single 0xFF character

The description of messages above says they "may involve bidirectional data
exchange", which means they're not really "messages" in the sense of packets
of data being sent in one direction; they're more like little sub-protocols.
I'm not sure what a better terminology would be; perhaps we can say that the
message is simply the byte pair (0xFF, message_type_id), and that when such
a "message" is sent & received, kernel and client immediately switch to the
corresponding sub-protocol, and then back to the "main" protocol when the
sub-protocol terminates.
Errr... let's go with that.

Here are the most important types of message sent by the client:
* GET_OFFSETS
  * initiated by client; kernel responds with some integer values, e.g.
    max number of tasks, task structure size, offset within task structure
    of heap etc -- things required when client is compiling tasklang code
* LOAD_TASK
  * client sends a task id
  * client sends the intended contents of the task's CODE and HEAP
  * kernel loads CODE and HEAP, and sets up the task's FIELDS such that
    it is in the stopped state (i.e. execution is paused until client
    sends START_TASK)
* START_TASK
  * client sends a task id
  * kernel begins execution of the indicated task from wherever it last
    left off (or from beginning, if task was freshly created)
* STOP_TASK
  * client sends a task id
  * kernel halts execution of the indicated task; its memory is left
    untouched, suitable for e.g. debugging with INSPECT_TASK or starting
    again with START_TASK
* INSPECT_TASK
  * client sends a task id
  * kernel sends the entire contents of the task's memory (i.e. its task_t
    structure)

Here are the most important types of message sent by the kernel:
* KERNEL_LOG
  * kernel sends a log message
* TASK_LOG
  * kernel sends a task id
  * kernel sends a log message
* TASK_STOPPED
  * kernel sends a task id
  * kernel sends a reason why task was stopped
    * 0: task stopped normally (e.g. reached the end of its code, or the
      tasklang "halt" instruction)
    * 1: failed assertion (tasklang "assert" instruction)
  * NOTE: this message is *not* sent when a task is stopped by the
    STOP_TASK message.

Note that this protocol has no error checking, or way to recover if the
parties get out of sync, so we are fully trusting the USB/USART infrastructure
to deliver our data perfectly every time!..


###############################################################################
### TASKLANG RUNTIME

The "tasklang" runtime is written in assembly.
It uses threaded code, i.e. code consists of arrays of pointers to subroutines.
The target architecture is the ATmega 328p, which is in the AVR family of
microchips, which share a common instruction set:
https://ww1.microchip.com/downloads/en/DeviceDoc/AVR-Instruction-Set-Manual-DS40002198A.pdf

In particular, the 328p uses 8-bit data words and 16-bit code addresses.
It's a RISC architecture: we have 32 8-bit registers (r0 through r31), with
many instructions performing an 8-bit operation in a single cycle.
The 8-bit registers naturally pair up into 16-bit pairs, e.g. r0:r1.
In particular, memory (SRAM) can only be accessed via specific register pairs:
X (r26:r27), Y (r28:r29), and Z (r30:r31).
Memory reads/writes are possible via X, Y and Z, but indirect jumps are only
possible via Z.
Therefore, the tasklang runtime uses Z as a pointer to the current instruction
within the threaded code.

The AVR architecture has a stack pointer, and dedicated stack intructions:
PUSH, POP, CALL, RET, and their variants.
The tasklang runtime uses this stack as well.
If tasklang were a proper FORTH, it would have a data stack and a call stack,
and so besides the architecture's built-in stack pointer, we would need to
choose between X and Y to implement the second stack.
However, we have avoided having to make this choice, by not bothering to
implement functions in tasklang!.. so it only has a data stack, which is
implemented using the architecture's stack, which is also used by subroutines
written in C and assembly.

(The reason FORTH requires two stacks is that one is used for function arguments
and return values, and the other is used for function return locations and
local variables.
Subroutines written in C and assembly get away with using 1 stack because they
can pass arguments and return values in registers.)

So, we've seen that:
* tasklang uses the Z register pair (r30:r31) to point to current instruction
  within threaded code (i.e. task's CODE memory section)
* tasklang uses the built-in stack as a data stack, and for calling C/asm
  routines (so, when a task is running, the stack pointer divides the task's
  FREE and STACK memory sections)

Now, what does the execution loop look like?..
Each tasklang instruction is implemented as an assembly routine.
E.g. the tasklang "+" instruction compiles to a pointer to the "add" routine.
The "add" routine is implemented something like this:

    add:

        ; pop a 16-bit value into the register pair r24:r25
        pop r25
        pop r24

        ; pop a 16-bit value into the register pair r22:r23
        pop r23
        pop r22

        ; add the two values together
        add r24, r22 ; add the lower bytes
        adc r25, r23 ; add the higher bytes with carry

        ; push the resulting 16-bit value
        push r24
        push r25

        ; jump to the "next" routine
        adiw r30, 2 ; increment Z by 2 bytes, the width of a pointer
        ijmp ; jump to the routine at which Z is now pointing

Some tasklang instructions take an argument, i.e. the threaded code contains
a code pointer followed by an argument.
For instance, integer literals use a subroutine like this:

    _literal:

        adiw r30, 2 ; increment Z by 2

        ; load the integer argument from threaded code into a register pair
        ld r24, Z
        ldd r25, Z+1

        ; push the integer argument onto the stack
        push r24
        push r25

        ; jump to the "next" routine (as did "add")
        adiw r30, 2
        ijmp

In some cases, e.g. the tasklang _jump instruction used for looping etc, the
argument may be a pointer to another threaded code instruction:

    _jump:

        adiw r30, 2 ; increment Z by 2

        ; load the argument (which is a pointer to another instruction within
        ; the threaded code)
        ld r24, Z
        ldd r25, Z+1

        ; copy the argument from register pair r24:r25 to r30:r31, i.e. Z
        movw r30, r24

        ; jump to the indicated instruction within the threaded code
        ijmp


