###############################################################################
### RESOURCE QUEUES

The OS considers the following things to be "resources" which tasks can use:
* the USB input/output streams
* other tasks' input/output streams (i.e. pipes)

Every resource is either an input stream or an output stream, and has an
associated queue.
Every task can be waiting on at most 1 queue. When the resource for that
queue becomes available, the first task in the queue is woken up.
If the resource was an input stream, its next byte of data is pushed onto
the woken task's stack.
If the resource was an output stream, a byte of data is popped from the
task's stack and sent through the output stream.

The microchip has a USART, which on the Arduino is hooked up to a serial-to-USB
chip (the FT232RL) which is hooked up to a mini-USB port.
This is the major shared resource in the "minitasks" OS; but there are also
"pipes", i.e. it's possible to connect tasks together and have them treat
each other as resources.

